Source: NZ Journal of Agriculture
Author:
Vol / Page: 141
Edition:
Quote: When a name for these intermediates is needed, the term "super-sickle" is used.
Notes:

Date: 20/3/1933
Source: NZ Journal of Agriculture
Author:
Vol / Page: 144
Edition:
Quote: Fibres of this kind that do not grow after birth are called "baby sickle-fibres."
Notes:

Date: 20/3/1933
Source: NZ Journal of Agriculture
Author:
Vol / Page: 145
Edition:
Quote: Other somewhat longer sickle-fibres, it would appear from their length, are shed after growing for just a short time after birth. These are termed "infant sickle-fibres" (Fig 4). Infant sickle-fibres are much less abundant than baby ones. Most sickle-fibres with coarse medulla in the post-natal region sustain this up to some eight weeks after birth. For these it is convenient to use the term "chalky sickle-fibres," from their dull white appearance. Super-sickle-fibres, some with a good deal of medulla in the neck, occasionally remain fine after birth ...
Notes:

Date: 20/6/1934
Source: NZ Journal of Agriculture
Author:
Vol / Page: 342
Edition:
Quote: The stoutest of birthcoat fibres, halo-hairs, are almost all shed and the super-sickle-fibres with necks coarser than those of sickle-fibres, shed the more readily.
